pullRequest.body:
The matter of whether `0` is or not a limit element (of the ordinals/cardinals) is a highly contentious one. To bridge this gap, we redefine `IsSuccLimit` so as to explicitly exclude minimal elements. A previous PR had already renamed the weaker notion to `IsSuccPrelimit`.

Future PRs will introduce the usual limit induction principles, and deprecate `Cardinal.IsLimit` and `Ordinal.IsLimit`.

Why is this primed. The first letter shouldn't be uppercased. Also do we need this lemma at all?
Hm, probably not.
useless diff?

Is this definitional?
```suggestion
theorem isSuccLimit_toDual_iff : IsSuccLimit (toDual a) â†” IsPredLimit a := .rfl
```
Nope, since the underlying `toDual_covBy_toDual_iff` isn't definitional either.
Should this be simp?
I don't think so; on the one hand `IsSuccLimit` provides strictly more information, but on the other, `IsSuccPrelimit` has a larger API.
I don't entirely agree, but that can be changed later

```suggestion
theorem isSuccLimit_toDual : IsSuccLimit (toDual a) â†” IsPredLimit a := by
```

This lemma name matches [`isSuccPrelimit_toDual_iff`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/SuccPred/Limit.html#Order.isSuccPrelimit_toDual_iff). Should I change that in another PR?
Yeah sure
